<section id="jackson-heart-study">
    <h2>The Jackson Heart Study</h2>

    <p>The <strong>Jackson Heart Study (JHS)</strong> is a landmark long-term research program studying cardiovascular disease in African Americans. Based in Jackson, Mississippi, it has followed over 5,000 participants since 2000.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Why Jackson?</h3>
        <p>Mississippi has one of the highest rates of cardiovascular disease in the nation, and Jackson's population provided an opportunity to study the unique factors affecting Black American heart health in depth.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Study Design</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Participants:</strong> 5,306 African Americans from the Jackson, MS metropolitan area</li>
        <li><strong>Age range:</strong> 21-95 years at enrollment</li>
        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Ongoing since 2000</li>
        <li><strong>Comprehensive data:</strong> Medical exams, blood tests, imaging, questionnaires, and community-level data</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Unique Features</h3>
    <p>Unlike most heart studies, JHS explicitly examines:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Discrimination:</strong> Experiences of racism and their health effects</li>
        <li><strong>Social context:</strong> Neighborhood, economics, social networks</li>
        <li><strong>Coping strategies:</strong> How people deal with stress</li>
        <li><strong>Cultural factors:</strong> Religion, community ties, resilience</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="research">
    <h2>Key Research Findings</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Dr. Taylor's Core Message</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "The Jackson Heart Study has taught us that you can't separate heart disease from the conditions in which people live. Discrimination, stress, access to healthy food, economic opportunity - these aren't just social issues, they're cardiovascular risk factors. We need to treat communities, not just individuals."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Major Findings from JHS</h3>

    <h4>1. Discrimination and Blood Pressure</h4>
    <p>Experiences of discrimination are associated with:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Higher blood pressure</li>
        <li>Greater likelihood of hypertension</li>
        <li>Less nocturnal blood pressure dipping (a risk factor for cardiovascular events)</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. John Henryism</h4>
    <p>High-effort coping with chronic stressors ("John Henryism" - named after the folk hero who worked himself to death) is linked to worse cardiovascular outcomes, especially in those with fewer resources.</p>

    <h4>3. Social Support is Protective</h4>
    <p>Strong social networks and community involvement are associated with:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Lower cardiovascular risk</li>
        <li>Better blood pressure control</li>
        <li>Improved survival after cardiac events</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>4. Food Environment Matters</h4>
    <p>Access to healthy food options significantly affects cardiovascular risk factors in the Jackson community.</p>

    <h4>5. Religious Participation</h4>
    <p>Church attendance and religious involvement show associations with better cardiovascular health in this population.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The Key Insight</h3>
        <p>Heart disease in Black Americans cannot be explained by genetics or individual behavior alone. Structural factors - residential segregation, economic inequality, healthcare access, and chronic stress from discrimination - are major drivers of disparities.</p>
    </div>
</section>

